    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "The easiest way to test this is to create a custom search client like this:\n\n```\nimport { SearchClient } from 'instantsearch.js';\n\nexport const searchClient: SearchClient = {\n   search(requests) {\n      return fetch(\"http://localhost:3000/api/search\", {\n         method: \"post\",\n         headers: {\n            \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\",\n         },\n         body: JSON.stringify({ requests }),\n      })\n         .then((res) => res.json())\n         .catch((err) => {\n            console.error(err);\n         });\n   },\n};\n```\n\nIn /api/search I throw an error to simulate a failed search. If catch is not added to waitForResults you will get the infinite page loading. If you handle the error (by adding a catch to waitForResults) and log it, you will see the same maximum call stack problem.",
